                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" id="aloe_sng_1" fkcefr="c2" hclass="sense"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">a tropical plant with thick leaves that have sharp points and that contain a lot of water. The juice of some types of <span class="dh">aloe</span> is used in medicine and <span class="ndv" xt="ndv" tofix="" href="cosmetic_topg_1">cosmetics</span>.</span></span><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/plants-and-trees?level=c2" title="Topic plants-and-trees"><span class="topic" href="l2:the_natural_world:plants_and_trees?cefr=c2"><span class="topic_name">Plants and trees</span><span class="topic_cefr">c2</span></span></a></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="aloe_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">Old English <span class="ei">alewe</span>, <span class="ei">alwe</span> (denoting the fragrant resin or the inner layers of wood of certain oriental trees), via Latin from Greek <span class="ei">aloē</span>; reinforced in late Middle English by Old French <span class="ei">aloes</span> ‘aloe’, hence frequently used in the plural.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
